Let's now calculate the future value of the first year discounting by five years since we're calculating the future value six years from now.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV}_{1} &=\$700\times{\left(1 + .01\right)^{5}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$700\times1.61051
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$1,127.36}
\end{aligned}$$

As can be seen above, the future value for the first year is $1,127.36.

Next, calculate the future value of the second year discounting by four years.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV}_{2} &=\$700\times{\left(1 + .01\right)^{4}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$700\times1.4641
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$1,024.87}
\end{aligned}$$

Hence, the future value for the second year is $1,024.87.

Let's now determine the future value for the third year.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV}_{3} &=\$800\times{\left(1 + .01\right)^{3}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$800\times1.331
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$1,064.80}
\end{aligned}$$

Therefore, the future value for the third year is $1,064.80.

Moving on, let's identify the future value for the fourth year.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV}_{4} &=\$800\times{\left(1 + .01\right)^{2}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$800\times1.21
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$968}
\end{aligned}$$

Thus, the future value of the fourth year is $968.

Next, calculate the future value for the fifth year.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV}_{5} &=\$900\times{\left(1 + .01\right)^{1}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$900\times1.1
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$990}
\end{aligned}$$

As can be seen in our calculation, the future value for the fifth year is $990.

Last, let's determine the future cash flow value in the sixth year.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV}_{6} &=\$900\times{\left(1 + .01\right)^{0}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$900\times1
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\$900}
\end{aligned}$$

Based on our calculation, the future value of the sixth year is $900.

Next, to determine the future value for the sixth year, we will combine the future values from the first to the sixth year. We will use the following formula in consolidating the future value.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{FV of Sixth Year}&={FV}_{1}+{FV}_{2}+{FV}_{3}+{FV}_{4}+{FV}_{5}+{FV}_{6}
\end{aligned}$$

We'll then discount the future value by 59 years because we've already calculated the future value for the first six years with a 10% interest rate of the policy's 65-year term. Let's calculate the remaining years to determine the future value of the future cash flows.

$$ \begin{aligned}
{FV} &=\$6,075.03\times{\left(1 + .07\right)^{59}}
\\[5pt]
&=\$6,075.03\times54.1555391
\\[5pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$328,996.36}
\end{aligned}$$

As a result of our computation, the future cash flows' future value considering the interest rate of 10% and 7% is $328,996.36.
